<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-297-176  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 297 176.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  Jan 23 1989 v3 n4 p28(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Neural networks fall short of miraculous but still work.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Reed, Fred.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Attitudes concerning neural networks range from messianicenthusiasm to unimpressed skepticism.andP;  Neural networks consist of'neurons,' which are small processing elements connected together,with each having many inputs and one output.andP;  Neural networkschief advantages are an ability to recognize patterns, to handlefuzzy data and to learn.andP;  The IRS, Postal Service and defensecontractors are three groups considering the networks for use inautomatic target recognition, in recognizing abnormal tax returnsand for reading handwritten ZIP codes.andP;  One success with neuralnetworks involved a project by the Defense Advanced ResearchProjects Agency, in which a Kanji recognizer for translatinghandwritten Japanese into English was developed.andP;  Despite thissuccess, the project found only four useful applications for therecognizer.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Neural NetworksResearch and DevelopmentApplicationsGoals and Objectives.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>